    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1988-01-29T21:03:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1988-01-29T21:03:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <head>273. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Morocco<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d273fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Foreign Policy File, Electronic Telegrams, D880081–0376. Confidential;
                        Immediate. Drafted by Ralph Winstanley (<gloss target="#t_NEAAFN_1"
                            >NEA/AFN</gloss>); cleared by William McGlynn (<gloss
                            target="#t_NEAECON_1">NEA/ECON</gloss>), Ralph Boyce (<gloss
                            target="#t_D_1">D</gloss>), Benjamin Pascoe (<gloss target="#t_SS_1"
                            >S/S</gloss>), and Carolyn Huggins (<gloss target="#t_SSO_1"
                            >S/S–O</gloss>); approved by <persName corresp="#p_UM_1"
                            >Ussery</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">28881.</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1988-01-30T02:03:00+00:00">January 30, 1988, 0203Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 88 Security Assistance Allocations for
                        Morocco: Special Talking Points.</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Confidential—Entire text.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>You will have received by septel final <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss>
                        88 security assistance figures for all countries and extensive talking
                        points for briefing host governments.<note n="2" xml:id="d273fn2">In
                            telegram 29684 to Vienna, February 4, which repeated telegram 29684 to
                            all American Republic diplomatic posts, February 3, the Department
                            outlined the approved <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 88 security
                            assistance allocations. (Department of State, Central Foreign Policy
                            File, Electronic Telegrams, D880624–0215)</note> The following points
                        may also be used in briefing the <gloss target="#t_GOM_1">GOM</gloss> on the
                        unique features of the Moroccan <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 88
                        program: <list>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Morocco did exceptionally, almost uniquely, well in a period of
                                major retrenchment;</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>Morocco’s <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 88 <gloss
                                    target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_MAP_1"
                                    >MAP</gloss>, and <gloss target="#t_FMS_1">FMS</gloss> total 72
                                million dollars compared with 54 million dollars in <gloss
                                    target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 87;</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>In comparison, the administration’s overall request was cut 14
                                percent and the net after earmarks was a 93 percent cut;</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>In 30 countries, security assistance will be eliminated; nearly
                                all countries, including very important ones, will take massive
                                cuts. For example, our <gloss target="#t_ESF_1">ESF</gloss> request
                                for Turkey of 120 million was cut to 32. The actual Turkish program
                                in 87 was 100 million. Jordan will receive 26.5 million of a
                                requested 40 million, a substantial cut from the 39.9 million <gloss
                                    target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 87 actual level;</item>
                            <label>—</label>
                            <item>In sum, these results show, if it needed to be shown, the high
                                regard with which Morocco is held in the U.S.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Shultz</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
